## Migration Analysis

Your code has three patterns that won't work in .NET 8:

| Pattern Found | Location | Issue in .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `ProcessLoop` | `Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| **ThreadAbortException catch** | `ProcessLoop` | Never thrown — cleanup logic silently lost |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | `ProcessLoop` | `SYSLIB0006` — obsolete, throws |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort equivalent needed. Just continue to let
                // the while-loop condition exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — cooperative, not preemptive.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when` guard ensures you only catch cancellation you initiated.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — the loop condition (`!token.IsCancellationRequested`) controls whether to continue. After rollback, the loop simply exits.
4. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(2s)`** — actually waits for completion instead of hoping.

## Critical: Update `GetNextItem`

If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it **must** accept the token — otherwise cancellation stalls until the next item arrives:

```csharp
// Before: blocks indefinitely, can't be interrupted
var item = _queue.Take();

// After: wakes immediately on cancellation
var item = _queue.Take(token); // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)
```

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing token to blocking calls** | `CancellationToken` can't interrupt `Thread.Sleep` or `socket.Receive`. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()`. |
| **Expecting instant cancellation** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it where you handle cleanup. Let it propagate elsewhere. |
